        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
Correlator Setep for 0.2" ALMA observations at 350 GHz: 0.2 km/s. 

In this band we have three basebands targeting spectral lines listed in Table 1 
of the propsoal.  More specifically these are C2H (349.3 GHz), C3H2 
(338.2 GHz), and H2CO (351.8 GHz).  The fourth baseband is dedicated to a 
continuum measurement. The line widths of this face on source are on the 
order of 1 km/s which drives the bandwidth for C2H and C3H2.  In the case of 
H2CO we have used lower spectral resolution (0.4 km/s) in order to capture 
the 9-8 line of C3H2.  The C2H line that drive the sensitivity estimate 
below also has hyperfine splitting with a total splitting on the order of 
1 km/s.  Thus this is resolved with 0.2 km/s or even smoothing to 0.4 km/s 
to gain signal-to-noise.


Requested Sensitivity for 0.2" ALMA observations at 350 GHz:
  
3 molecular lines and one continuum setting are requested within this 
science goal. Of these only C2H has been detected in spatially 
unresolved observations from APEX (Kastner et al. 2013), with a total 
peak flux of 4 Jy.  The spatial distribution of this emission within the 
source is unknown.  Thus we assume that it is similar to that of the N2H+ 
emission (J = 4-3) recently published by Qi et al. 2013 (Science, 341, 630).  
N2H+ has a similar critical density to C2H and the upper state energy 
(44.7 K, N2H+; 41.9 K, C2H) is similarly comparable.  In this intance 
the ALMA observations with a 0.6" beam resolved the source with the 
primary emission confined to an area of 1.8".  Thus if we assume that 
the C2H emission is spread evenly throughout that spatial region then 
in a 0.2" beam the flux would be (0.2/1.8)^2 x 4 Jy = 50 mJy.  

Based on this estimate in 2.0 hours we can achieve an rms sensitivity 
of 7.5 mJy in 0.2 km/s channels for a 7 sigma detection.  Morevoer, we 
can lower the velocity resolution to 0.4 km/s to achive detections at 
the 10sigma level.

Imaging requirements:
We request observations with two 12m array configurations to achive 
sensitivity to scales of 0.2" (11 AU) and to the outer disk.  This program 
seeks to explore chemical gradients in this system and this spatial resolution 
will place one pixel on the predicted midplane snowline for these tracers, 
with several pixels covering the surface snowline.   The additional more 
compact 12m array configuration allows sensitivity to the outer disk surface 
which is critial for drawing connections to the inner disk and also to 
abundance measurements from unresolved observations and to the ISM.

The continuum flux of 250 mJy is estimated from the ~0.6" angular resolution 
observations of TW Hya at 870 microns by Andrews et al. 2012, ApJ, 744, 162.
The surface density generally scales as 1/r with
surface area going as r^2.  Thus we assume the continuum scales with
radius giving ~82 mJy
Thus the expected line rms to continuum is 7.5mJy/82 mJy or 1:10.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
