        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>
Correlator Setep for 0.4" ALMA observations of DM Tau at 260 GHz: 0.3 km/s. 

In this band we have three basebands targeting spectral lines listed in Table 1 
of the propsoal.  More specifically these are C2H (262.0 GHz), C3H2 (244.2 GHz),
and CH3OH (243.9 GHz).  The fourth baseband is dedicated to a continuum 
measurement. The line widths of this source are on the order of 1-3 km/s in 
the outer disk which determines the bandwidth for C2H and C3H2.    The C2H 
line that drive the sensitivity estimate below also has hyperfine splitting 
with a total splitting on the order of &gt; 1 km/s.  Thus this is resolved with 
0.3 km/s or even smoothing to 0.6 km/s to gain signal-to-noise.

Requested Sensitivity for 0.4" ALMA observations at 260 GHz:

Detected CCH emission is used to set our sensitivity to gaurantee a result.

Peak flux CCH 2-1 is 0.3 Jy and unresolved in ~2.6" beam from Henning et al. 
(2010). They derive a low excitation tempearture (~8 K) for the outer disk at 
300 AU.  We will observe the 3-2 transition at 261 GHz.  Based on excitaiton 
calculations, assuming  optically thin emission (worse case), then the flux 
of the 3-2 transition will be 2x higher than the 2-1.  The 2-1 transition 
observed from the Plateau du Bure is unresolved and we assume that the flux 
is concentrated in the inner 1.5".  Thus the expected flux is 0.6 Jy * 
(0.4/1.5)^2 = 42 mJy.  
In 2.0 hours we can expect a 10sigma detection in a 0.4" beam.



Imaging requirements:
We request observations with two 12m array configurations to achive 
sensitivity to scales of 0.4" (60 AU) and to the outer disk.  This program 
seeks to explore chemical gradients in this system and compare to the closer 
TW Hya disk.   The additional more compact 12m array configuration allows 
sensitivity to the outer disk surface which is critial for drawing connections 
to the inner disk and also to abundance measurements from unresolved 
observations and to the ISM.

A continuum flux of 130 mJy in a ~3" beam angular resolution is taken
from Oberg et al. 2010.  The surface density generally scales as 1/r with
surface area going as r^2.  Thus we assume the continuum scales with
radius and the continuum in a 0.4" beam would be 17 mJy and a line
rms of 4 mJy.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
