        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>

Correlator Setep for 0.4" ALMA observations of DM Tau at 329 GHz: 0.3 km/s. 

In this band we have three basebands targeting spectral lines listed in Table 1 
of the propsoal.  More specifically these are 13CO (3-2; 330.6), C18O 
(3-2; 329.4 GHz), CH3OH (340.2 GHz).  The fourth baseband is dedicated to a 
continuum measurement. The line widths of this source are on the order of 
1-3 km/s in the outer disk which drives the bandwidth.

Requested Sensitivity for 0.4" ALMA observations at 329 GHz:

Here the main goal is a C18O 3-2 detection which determines our sensitivity 
goal.

The peak flux C18O 2-1 is 2 K in a 1.6" beam (marginally resolved) from 
Dartois et al. 2003, A&amp;A. We assume that that flux in C18O 3-2 is comparable 
to the 2-1 (an average excitation tempeature of 20-30 K in the emissive 
layers). In 51 minutes we can achieve an rms of 100 mK or 20:1 S/N.  This 
time estiamte includes 2 12m array configurations to obtain sensitivity to 
large and small angular scles. 
 


Imaging requirements:
We request observations with two 12m array configurations to achive 
sensitivity to scales of 0.4" (60 AU) and to the outer disk.  This program 
seeks to explore chemical gradients in this system and compare to the closer 
TW Hya disk.   The additional more compact 12m array configuration allows 
sensitivity to the outer disk surface which is critial for drawing 
connections to the inner disk and also to abundance measurements from 
unresolved observations and to the ISM.

A continuum flux of 143 mJy in a ~3" beam angular resolution at 267 GHz is taken
from Oberg et al. 2010.  Scaling this to 329 GHz with 
beta = 1 gives 267 Jy. The surface density generally scales as 1/r with
surface area going as r^2.  Thus we assume the continuum scales with
radius and the continuum in a 0.4" beam would be 35 mJy with a
line rms of a 1.5 mJy</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
